# Automation Improvement Review Loop

When Thien asks to improve, update, refactor, clarify, redesign, or otherwise
change a Codex automation, follow this workflow:

1. Read the current automation content and the exact new requirement.
2. Give the current automation and requirement to Claude AI and ask Claude AI to
   provide an updated automation proposal, not only feedback.
3. Send Claude AI's updated proposal to Cursor Agent. Ask Cursor Agent to
   criticize it for ambiguity, missing gates, unsafe ownership, conflicting
   instructions, and practical execution issues, then return an improved
   proposal.
4. Send Cursor Agent's proposal back to Claude AI. Ask Claude AI to criticize it
   and return another improved proposal.
5. Send Claude AI's second proposal back to Cursor Agent. Ask Cursor Agent to
   provide final critique notes and, when useful, a final edited proposal.
6. Let Codex make the final decision, resolve conflicts, apply the final
   automation update, validate syntax/metadata, save it, and sync it.

Ownership rules:

- Codex remains the final editor and synchronization owner.
- Claude AI and Cursor Agent are reviewers/proposal generators unless Thien
  explicitly authorizes a separate manual editing session.
- If Claude AI or Cursor Agent is unavailable, unauthenticated, times out, or
  returns unusable output, record that concrete failure and continue only when
  the user requirement can still be satisfied safely.
- Save the updated automation in `~/.codex/automations/<automation_id>/automation.toml`.
- Sync changed automations to `/Users/thien.nguyen/thiennp.github.io/codex-automations/`
  when the mirror exists or the automation sync workflow applies.
- Commit and push the shared `thiennp.github.io` repo when sync changes are made
  and it is safe to do so.
